    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "Homeowner Opportunities -",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H2",
      "text": "Richmond, VA – Virginia’s Neighborhood Stabilization Program (NSP) is turning vacant, foreclosed",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "and potentially blighting homes into homeownership opportunities for Virginia’s low, moderate and",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "middle income families.",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "“The NSP has provided an opportunity for communities to address the impacts of foreclosure, to",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "stabilize home prices, and prevent homes from becoming sources of blight,” said DHCD Director Bill",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "Shelton.  “However the program is also focused on making these homes available for low, moderate",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "and middle income families.”",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "Area homebuyers earning up to 120 percent of the area median income are encouraged to find out if",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "they are eligible.  Eligible homebuyers may receive closing cost and other assistance to help make the",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "homes affordable.  NSP funds must be used by September 17, 2010, and prospective homebuyers are",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "urged to contact NSP grantees to find out more.  Many grantees are now concentrating on identifying",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "and qualifying eligible homebuyers in those areas of Virginia served by the NSP.",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "NSP grantees are providing assistance in the following areas of the Commonwealth:",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H2",
      "text": "Northern Virginia: Alexandria, Loudoun, Fauquier, Fairfax, Stafford, Prince William, Manassas,",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "Fredericksburg, Caroline, Spotsylvania, Culpeper, Orange",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H2",
      "text": "Central Virginia: Richmond City, Chesterfield, Louisa, Lynchburg, Petersburg",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H2",
      "text": "Tidewater/Hampton Roads: Newport News, Hampton, Norfolk, Chesapeake, Suffolk,",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "Portsmouth, Virginia Beach",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H2",
      "text": "Northern Shenandoah:  Warren, Frederick, Shenandoah, Winchester",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H2",
      "text": "Southside: Franklin County, Danville",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H2",
      "text": "Southwest:  Bristol",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "Through the NSP, 22 local government and nonprofit organizations have been working to acquire",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "foreclosed properties at a discounted rate, rehabilitate them and make them available for resale to",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H1",
      "text": "qualified homebuyers earning up to 120 percent of the area median income.",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H3",
      "text": "The NSP was authorized under the Housing and Economic Recovery Act (HERA) of 2008 to provide",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H3",
      "text": "emergency assistance to state and local governments in acquiring and redeveloping vacant and foreclosed",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H3",
      "text": "properties that might otherwise become sources of abandonment and blight within their communities.",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H3",
      "text": "- more -",
      "page": 1
    },
    {
      "level": "H2",
      "text": "The Virginia Department of Housing and Community Development (DHCD) is administering Virginia’s",
      "page": 2
    },
    {
      "level": "H3",
      "text": "NSP, and has received $38.7 million in funding from the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban",
      "page": 2
    },
    {
      "level": "H3",
      "text": "Development for this program. Grant funds have been allocated through DHCD to local governments and",
      "page": 2
    },
    {
      "level": "H3",
      "text": "certified nonprofits, which are negotiating the purchase of homes.  All properties must be acquired at a",
      "page": 2
    },
    {
      "level": "H3",
      "text": "minimum of one percent below as-is appraised value.",
      "page": 2
    },
    {
      "level": "H3",
      "text": "To-date, approximately 70 homes have been purchased by grantees through the program, with many more",
      "page": 2
    },
    {
      "level": "H3",
      "text": "to follow.  More information about this program can be obtained by contacting the Virginia NSP",
      "page": 2
    },
    {
      "level": "H3",
      "text": "administrator in your area of interest.",
      "page": 2
